Title: Linking forum posts - classical-HW-001-9-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Week 2 assignment solution arpeggio error or fashion?
Input.posts:
hello everybody. In the fifth measure and first tempo of the arpeggiated texture there are not exactly the same notes of the keyboard voicing. In keyboard voicing we have CGC in TAS and in the arpeggiated texture, they changed to GCGE instead of GCGC....... is an error or is to avoid the large leaps in the arpeggio?... or only to make it more fashion with the third of the chord?.......
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Fernando. It is not an error. That chord in question is essentially chord i. While it is correct to do GCGC for the arpeggiation, it makes more sense to arpeggiate with an added Eb after the G, to avoid the large leaps as mentioned. You should treat the keyboard voicing as sort of a textural reduction to the arpeggiated texture exercise.
Instructor's post : Hi Fernando. It is not an error. That chord in question is essentially chord i. Oh, and the keyboard part 2 http://www.noteflight.com/scores/view/d6e10bcf1e4259d082367bb2419f703ee0e01a58
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Alexander. Anonymous is right. You have a parallel fifth from measure 7 to 8 in the bass and alto.  With regard to the missing thirds in measure 10 chord V and measure 11 chord V7, this is definitely unacceptable as the thirds in chords are important to define its identity (whether it being a major or minor chord). You need to have them in. For measure 10 chord V, it is best that you change the alto to a G and the tenor to B natural. If you do this, then check the next chord - switch the alto and tenor notes so that you can get a smoother voicing. As for the V7 chord in measure 11, you have the seventh and the doubled root. You can change the tenor to a B natural to accommodate for the missing third.

Hi Alexander. There are only a few discrepancies that I can see with your solution against the given solution. This is avoided, from a practical point of view, because an interval of a seventh is not easy to sing, therefore a better option would be to take a step up to the G before going down an octave. It is better if you could double the root instead by changing the tenor to a C. Lastly, for the first i chord of measure 12, you chose to voice lead the previous B natural into C, which is acceptable, even though the chord becomes incomplete.

Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Reis, I like that you unleashed a little bit of creativity in bar 4. However, like Alberto pointed out, in the second i chord of that bar, the distance between tenor and alto is greater than the octave and by doing so, you have compromised the sonority of the chord. So it's better to keep the i chord the same. About the notes in parenthesis that come after that, I think you meant them as non-chord tones. But I'd like to point out that that chord would be labeled as a i6-4 instead, as you have essentially created a pedal 6-4 chord that voice leads nicely between the first i of bar 4 and the next i in bar 5.  It would have been correct if the assignment asked for that, but unfortunately it doesn't. Good application of the 6-4 chord though.

Good application of the 6-4 chord though.

Input.posts:
In measure four of the keyboard voicing assignment on page 2, when the chord changes from V to V4/2, does the added seventh to the chord require moving all of the other parts?  When I completed the assignment, I simply moved the bass note down to the seventh and left the three treble voices where they were.  Is this considered a parallel fifths situation, or did the professor move the upper three voices for another reason?  I'm just curious, since the move caused leaps for the alto.  
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Katie. Your answer would still be correct. It is not considered as a parallel fifth as the notes of the two chords do not move. I believe Dr Edwards move the upper three voices to add variety. Also, as we are no longer in vocal four-part voicing, but in keyboard voicing, the leap in the 'alto' voice is not an issue.
